# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lie-algebras
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] In mathematics, a **Cartan subalgebra**, often abbreviated as **CSA**, is a nilpotent subalgebra ${\mathfrak {h}}$ of a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ that is self-normalising (if $[X,Y]\in {\mathfrak {h}}$ for all $X\in {\mathfrak {h}}$ , then $Y\in {\mathfrak {h}}$ ).
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] They were introduced by Élie Cartan in his doctoral thesis, and control the representation theory of a semi-simple Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over a field of characteristic 0 .
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] In general, a subalgebra is called toral if it consists of semisimple elements.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Over an algebraically closed field, a toral subalgebra is automatically abelian.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Thus, over an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero, a Cartan subalgebra can also be defined as a maximal toral subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Kac–Moody algebras and generalized Kac–Moody algebras also have subalgebras that play the same role as the Cartan subalgebras of semisimple Lie algebras (over a field of characteristic zero).
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Cartan subalgebras exist for finite-dimensional Lie algebras whenever the base field is infinite.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] One way to construct a Cartan subalgebra is by means of a regular element.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Over a finite field, the question of the existence is still open.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] A Cartan subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is then the same thing as a maximal toral subalgebra and the existence of a maximal toral subalgebra is easy to see.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] In a finite-dimensional Lie algebra over an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero, all Cartan subalgebras are conjugate under automorphisms of the algebra, and in particular are all isomorphic.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] The common dimension of a Cartan subalgebra is then called the rank of the algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] For a finite-dimensional complex semisimple Lie algebra, the existence of a Cartan subalgebra is much simpler to establish, assuming the existence of a compact real form.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] In that case, ${\mathfrak {h}}$ may be taken as the complexification of the Lie algebra of a maximal torus of the compact group.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] If ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a linear Lie algebra (a Lie subalgebra of the Lie algebra of endomorphisms of a finite-dimensional vector space *V*) over an algebraically closed field, then any Cartan subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is the centralizer of a maximal toral subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] If ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is semisimple and the field has characteristic zero, then a maximal toral subalgebra is self-normalizing, and so is equal to the associated Cartan subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] If in addition ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is semisimple, then the adjoint representation presents ${\mathfrak {g}}$ as a linear Lie algebra, so that a subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is Cartan if and only if it is a maximal toral subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Then $\Phi$ is a root system and, moreover, ${\mathfrak {g}}_{0}={\mathfrak {h}}$ ; i.e., the centralizer of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ coincides with ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] See also Semisimple Lie algebra#Structure for further information.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Given a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over a field of characteristic 0 , and a Lie algebra representation ${\displaystyle \sigma$ there is a decomposition related to the decomposition of the Lie algebra from its Cartan subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] But, it turns out these weights can be used to classify the irreducible representations of the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] For a finite dimensional irreducible ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -representation V , there exists a unique weight $\lambda \in \Phi$ with respect to a partial ordering on ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Moreover, given a $\lambda \in \Phi$ such that $\langle \alpha ,\lambda \rangle \in \mathbb {N}$ for every positive root $\alpha \in \Phi ^{+}$ , there exists a unique irreducible representation $L^{+}(\lambda )$ .
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Over non-algebraically closed fields, not all Cartan subalgebras are conjugate.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Over a non-algebraically closed field not every semisimple Lie algebra is splittable, however.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] A Cartan subgroup of a Lie group is a special type of subgroup.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Specifically, its Lie algebra (which captures the group’s algebraic structure) is itself a Cartan subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] When we consider the identity component of a subgroup, it shares the same Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] However, there isn’t a universally agreed-upon definition for which subgroup with this property should be called the ‘Cartan subgroup,’ especially when dealing with disconnected groups.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] For compact connected Lie groups, a Cartan subgroup is essentially a maximal connected Abelian subgroup—often referred to as a ‘maximal torus.’ The Lie algebra associated with this subgroup is also a Cartan subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] Now, when we explore disconnected compact Lie groups, things get interesting.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] There are multiple definitions for a Cartan subgroup.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] One common approach, proposed by David Vogan, defines it as the group of elements that normalize a fixed maximal torus while preserving the fundamental Weyl chamber.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] This version is sometimes called the ‘large Cartan subgroup.’ Additionally, there exists a ‘small Cartan subgroup,’ defined as the centralizer of a maximal torus.
[src:lie-algebras/cartan-subalgebra] It’s important to note that these Cartan subgroups may not always be abelian in general.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] In mathematics, the **Killing form**, named after Wilhelm Killing, is a symmetric bilinear form that plays a basic role in the theories of Lie groups and Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Cartan's criteria (criterion of solvability and criterion of semisimplicity) show that Killing form has a close relationship to the semisimplicity of the Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The Killing form was essentially introduced into Lie algebra theory by Élie Cartan (1894) in his thesis.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] In a historical survey of Lie theory, Borel (2001) has described how the term *"Killing form"* first occurred in 1951 during one of his own reports for the Séminaire Bourbaki; it arose as a misnomer, since the form had previously been used by Lie theorists, without a name attached.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Some other authors now employ the term *"Cartan-Killing form"*.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] A basic result that Cartan made use of was Cartan's criterion, which states that the Killing form is non-degenerate if and only if the Lie algebra is a direct sum of simple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Consider a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over a field *K*.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] with values in *K*, the **Killing form** on ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The following properties follow as theorems from the above definition.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] in Einstein summation notation, where the *c**ij**k* are the structure coefficients of the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The index *k* functions as column index and the index *n* as row index in the matrix ad(*e**i*)ad(*e**j*).
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The Killing form is the simplest 2-tensor that can be formed from the structure constants.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] In the above indexed definition, we are careful to distinguish upper and lower indices (*co-* and *contra-variant* indices).
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] This is because, in many cases, the Killing form can be used as a metric tensor on a manifold, in which case the distinction becomes an important one for the transformation properties of tensors.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] When the Lie algebra is semisimple over a zero-characteristic field, its Killing form is nondegenerate, and hence can be used as a metric tensor to raise and lower indexes.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] In this case, it is always possible to choose a basis for ${\mathfrak {g}}$ such that the structure constants with all upper indices are completely antisymmetric.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The table shows that the Dynkin index for the adjoint representation is equal to twice the dual Coxeter number.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Suppose that ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a semisimple Lie algebra over the field of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] By Cartan's criterion, the Killing form is nondegenerate, and can be diagonalized in a suitable basis with the diagonal entries ±1.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] By Sylvester's law of inertia, the number of positive entries is an invariant of the bilinear form, i.e. it does not depend on the choice of the diagonalizing basis, and is called the **index** of the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] This is a number between 0 and the dimension of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ which is an important invariant of the real Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] In particular, a real Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is called **compact** if the Killing form is negative definite (or negative semidefinite if the Lie algebra is not semisimple).
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Note that this is one of two inequivalent definitions commonly used for compactness of a Lie algebra; the other states that a Lie algebra is compact if it corresponds to a compact Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The definition of compactness in terms of negative definiteness of the Killing form is more restrictive, since using this definition it can be shown that under the Lie correspondence, compact Lie algebras correspond to compact semisimple Lie groups.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] If ${\mathfrak {g}}_{\mathbb {C} }$ is a semisimple Lie algebra over the complex numbers, then there are several non-isomorphic real Lie algebras whose complexification is ${\mathfrak {g}}_{\mathbb {C} }$ , which are called its **real forms**.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] It turns out that every complex semisimple Lie algebra admits a unique (up to isomorphism) compact real form ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The real forms of a given complex semisimple Lie algebra are frequently labeled by the positive index of inertia of their Killing form.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] For example, the complex special linear algebra ${\mathfrak {sl}}(2,\mathbb {C} )$ has two real forms, the real special linear algebra, denoted ${\mathfrak {sl}}(2,\mathbb {R} )$ , and the special unitary algebra, denoted ${\mathfrak {su}}(2)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The first one is noncompact, the so-called **split real form**, and its Killing form has signature (2, 1).
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The second one is the compact real form and its Killing form is negative definite, i.e. has signature (0, 3).
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] The corresponding Lie groups are the noncompact group $\mathrm {SL} (2,\mathbb {R} )$ of 2 × 2 real matrices with the unit determinant and the special unitary group $\mathrm {SU} (2)$ , which is compact.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be a finite-dimensional Lie algebra over the field K , and ${\displaystyle \rho$ be a Lie algebra representation.
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Let ${\text{Tr}}_{V}:{\text{End}}(V)\rightarrow K$ be the trace functional on V .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] Then the Killing form is the special case that the representation is the adjoint representation, ${\text{Tr}}_{\text{ad}}=B$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] It is easy to show that this is symmetric, bilinear and invariant for any representation $\rho$ .
[src:lie-algebras/killing-form] If furthermore ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is simple and $\rho$ is irreducible, then it can be shown ${\text{Tr}}_{\rho }=I(\rho )B$ where $I(\rho )$ is the index of the representation.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In mathematics, a **Lie algebra** (pronounced /liː/ *LEE*) is a vector space ${\mathfrak {g}}$ together with an operation called the **Lie bracket**, an alternating bilinear map ${\mathfrak {g}}\times {\mathfrak {g}}\rightarrow {\mathfrak {g}}$ , that satisfies the Jacobi identity.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In other words, a Lie algebra is an algebra over a field for which the multiplication operation (called the Lie bracket) is alternating and satisfies the Jacobi identity.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie bracket of two vectors x and y is denoted $[x,y]$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra is typically a non-associative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] However, every associative algebra gives rise to a Lie algebra, consisting of the same vector space with the commutator Lie bracket, $[x,y]=xy-yx$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Lie algebras are closely related to Lie groups, which are groups that are also smooth manifolds: every Lie group gives rise to a Lie algebra, which is the tangent space at the identity.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (In this case, the Lie bracket measures the failure of commutativity for the Lie group.) Conversely, to any finite-dimensional Lie algebra over the real or complex numbers, there is a corresponding connected Lie group, unique up to covering spaces (Lie's third theorem).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This correspondence allows one to study the structure and classification of Lie groups in terms of Lie algebras, which are simpler objects of linear algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In more detail: for any Lie group, the multiplication operation near the identity element 1 is commutative to first order.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In other words, every Lie group *G* is (to first order) approximately a real vector space, namely the tangent space ${\mathfrak {g}}$ to *G* at the identity.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] To second order, the group operation may be non-commutative, and the second-order terms describing the non-commutativity of *G* near the identity give ${\mathfrak {g}}$ the structure of a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] It is a remarkable fact that these second-order terms (the Lie algebra) completely determine the group structure of *G* near the identity.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] They even determine *G* globally, up to covering spaces.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In physics, Lie groups appear as symmetry groups of physical systems, and their Lie algebras (tangent vectors near the identity) may be thought of as infinitesimal symmetry motions.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Thus Lie algebras and their representations are used extensively in physics, notably in quantum mechanics and particle physics.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This is the Lie algebra of the Lie group of rotations of space, and each vector $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ may be pictured as an infinitesimal rotation around the axis v , with angular speed equal to the magnitude of v .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie bracket is a measure of the non-commutativity between two rotations.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Since a rotation commutes with itself, one has the alternating property $[x,x]=x\times x=0$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A fundamental example of a Lie algebra is the space of all linear maps from a vector space to itself, as discussed below.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] When the vector space has dimension *n*, this Lie algebra is called the **general linear** Lie algebra, ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Equivalently, this is the space of all $n\times n$ matrices.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie bracket is defined to be the commutator of matrices (or linear maps), $[X,Y]=XY-YX$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Lie algebras were introduced to study the concept of infinitesimal transformations by Sophus Lie in the 1870s, and independently discovered by Wilhelm Killing in the 1880s.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The name *Lie algebra* was given by Hermann Weyl in the 1930s; in older texts, the term *infinitesimal group* was used.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Given a Lie group, the Jacobi identity for its Lie algebra follows from the associativity of the group operation.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Using bilinearity to expand the Lie bracket $[x+y,x+y]$ and using the alternating property shows that $[x,y]+[y,x]=0$ for all $x,y$ in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] It is customary to denote a Lie algebra by a lower-case fraktur letter such as ${\mathfrak {g,h,b,n}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] If a Lie algebra is associated with a Lie group, then the algebra is denoted by the fraktur version of the group's name: for example, the Lie algebra of SU(*n*) is ${\mathfrak {su}}(n)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The *dimension* of a Lie algebra over a field means its dimension as a vector space.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In physics, a vector space basis of the Lie algebra of a Lie group G may be called a set of *generators* for G .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (They are "infinitesimal generators" for G , so to speak.) In mathematics, a set S of *generators* for a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ means a subset of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ such that any Lie subalgebra (as defined below) that contains S must be all of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Equivalently, ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is spanned (as a vector space) by all iterated brackets of elements of S .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra is called **abelian** if its Lie bracket is identically zero.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Any vector space V endowed with the identically zero Lie bracket becomes a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Every one-dimensional Lie algebra is abelian, by the alternating property of the Lie bracket.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] ), where the group operation is matrix multiplication.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] describes the failure of commutativity for matrix multiplication, or equivalently for the composition of linear maps.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie bracket is not required to be associative, meaning that $[[x,y],z]$ need not be equal to $[x,[y,z]]$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Nonetheless, much of the terminology for associative rings and algebras (and also for groups) has analogs for Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A **Lie subalgebra** is a linear subspace ${\mathfrak {h}}\subseteq {\mathfrak {g}}$ which is closed under the Lie bracket.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In the correspondence between Lie groups and Lie algebras, subgroups correspond to Lie subalgebras, and normal subgroups correspond to ideals.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] An **isomorphism** of Lie algebras is a bijective homomorphism.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] As with normal subgroups in groups, ideals in Lie algebras are precisely the kernels of homomorphisms.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Given a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ and an ideal ${\mathfrak {i}}$ in it, the *quotient Lie algebra* ${\mathfrak {g}}/{\mathfrak {i}}$ is defined, with a surjective homomorphism ${\mathfrak {g}}\to {\mathfrak {g}}/{\mathfrak {i}}$ of Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The first isomorphism theorem holds for Lie algebras: for any homomorphism $\varphi \colon {\mathfrak {g}}\to {\mathfrak {h}}$ of Lie algebras, the image of $\varphi$ is a Lie subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ that is isomorphic to ${\mathfrak {g}}/\ker(\varphi )$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For the Lie algebra of a Lie group, the Lie bracket is a kind of infinitesimal commutator.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] As a result, for any Lie algebra, two elements $x,y\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ are said to *commute* if their bracket vanishes: $[x,y]=0$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The centralizer subalgebra of a subset $S\subset {\mathfrak {g}}$ is the set of elements commuting with *S*: that is, ${\mathfrak {z}}_{\mathfrak {g}}(S)=\{x\in {\mathfrak {g}}:[x,s]=0\ {\text{ for all }}s\in S\}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The centralizer of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ itself is the *center* ${\mathfrak {z}}({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Similarly, for a subspace *S*, the normalizer subalgebra of *S* is ${\mathfrak {n}}_{\mathfrak {g}}(S)=\{x\in {\mathfrak {g}}:[x,s]\in S\ {\text{ for all}}\ s\in S\}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] If S is a Lie subalgebra, ${\mathfrak {n}}_{\mathfrak {g}}(S)$ is the largest subalgebra such that S is an ideal of ${\mathfrak {n}}_{\mathfrak {g}}(S)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The subspace ${\mathfrak {t}}_{n}$ of diagonal matrices in ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n,F)$ is an abelian Lie subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (It is a Cartan subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n)$ , analogous to a maximal torus in the theory of compact Lie groups.) Here ${\mathfrak {t}}_{n}$ is not an ideal in ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n)$ for $n\geq 2$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Every one-dimensional linear subspace of a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is an abelian Lie subalgebra, but it need not be an ideal.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This is the product in the category of Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be a Lie algebra and ${\mathfrak {i}}$ an ideal of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] See also semidirect sum of Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (The definition makes sense for a possibly non-associative algebra.) Given two derivations $D_{1}$ and $D_{2}$ , their commutator $[D_{1},D_{2}]:=D_{1}D_{2}-D_{2}D_{1}$ is again a derivation.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This operation makes the space ${\text{Der}}_{F}(A)$ of all derivations of *A* over *F* into a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Informally speaking, the space of derivations of *A* is the Lie algebra of the automorphism group of *A*.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (This is literally true when the automorphism group is a Lie group, for example when *F* is the real numbers and *A* has finite dimension as a vector space.) For this reason, spaces of derivations are a natural way to construct Lie algebras: they are the "infinitesimal automorphisms" of *A*.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (where 1 denotes the identity map on *A*) gives exactly the definition of *D* being a derivation.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra can be viewed as a non-associative algebra, and so each Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over a field *F* determines its Lie algebra of derivations, ${\text{Der}}_{F}({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The *inner derivation* associated to any $x\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ is the adjoint mapping $\mathrm {ad} _{x}$ defined by $\mathrm {ad} _{x}(y):=[x,y]$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (This is a derivation as a consequence of the Jacobi identity.) That gives a homomorphism of Lie algebras, $\operatorname {ad} \colon {\mathfrak {g}}\to {\text{Der}}_{F}({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (This is exactly analogous to the outer automorphism group of a group.) For a semisimple Lie algebra (defined below) over a field of characteristic zero, every derivation is inner.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This is related to the theorem that the outer automorphism group of a semisimple Lie group is finite.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In contrast, an abelian Lie algebra has many outer derivations.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Namely, for a vector space V with Lie bracket zero, the Lie algebra ${\text{Out}}_{F}(V)$ can be identified with ${\mathfrak {gl}}(V)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A matrix group is a Lie group consisting of invertible matrices, $G\subset \mathrm {GL} (n,\mathbb {R} )$ , where the group operation of *G* is matrix multiplication.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie bracket of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is given by the commutator of matrices, $[X,Y]=XY-YX$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Given a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}\subset {\mathfrak {gl}}(n,\mathbb {R} )$ , one can recover the Lie group as the subgroup generated by the matrix exponential of elements of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (To be precise, this gives the identity component of *G*, if *G* is not connected.) Here the exponential mapping $\exp :M_{n}(\mathbb {R} )\to M_{n}(\mathbb {R} )$ is defined by $\exp(X)=I+X+{\tfrac {1}{2!}}X^{2}+{\tfrac {1}{3!}}X^{3}+\cdots$ , which converges for every matrix X .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The same comments apply to complex Lie subgroups of $\operatorname {GL} (n,\mathbb {C} )$ and the complex matrix exponential, $\exp :M_{n}(\mathbb {C} )\to M_{n}(\mathbb {C} )$ (defined by the same formula).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Here are some matrix Lie groups and their Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Some Lie algebras of low dimension are described here.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] See the classification of low-dimensional real Lie algebras for further examples.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] can be broken into abelian "pieces", meaning that it is solvable (though not nilpotent), in the terminology below.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] is simple, and classify its finite-dimensional representations (defined below).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Given a vector space *V*, let ${\mathfrak {gl}}(V)$ denote the Lie algebra consisting of all linear maps from *V* to itself, with bracket given by $[X,Y]=XY-YX$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] That is, $\pi$ sends each element of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ to a linear map from *V* to itself, in such a way that the Lie bracket on ${\mathfrak {g}}$ corresponds to the commutator of linear maps.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A representation is said to be *faithful* if its kernel is zero.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Ado's theorem states that every finite-dimensional Lie algebra over a field of characteristic zero has a faithful representation on a finite-dimensional vector space.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Kenkichi Iwasawa extended this result to finite-dimensional Lie algebras over a field of any characteristic.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Equivalently, every finite-dimensional Lie algebra over a field *F* is isomorphic to a Lie subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n,F)$ for some positive integer *n*.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] One important aspect of the study of Lie algebras (especially semisimple Lie algebras, as defined below) is the study of their representations.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Although Ado's theorem is an important result, the primary goal of representation theory is not to find a faithful representation of a given Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Indeed, in the semisimple case, the adjoint representation is already faithful.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Rather, the goal is to understand all possible representations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For a semisimple Lie algebra over a field of characteristic zero, Weyl's theorem says that every finite-dimensional representation is a direct sum of irreducible representations (those with no nontrivial invariant subspaces).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The finite-dimensional irreducible representations are well understood from several points of view; see the representation theory of semisimple Lie algebras and the Weyl character formula.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The functor that takes an associative algebra *A* over a field *F* to *A* as a Lie algebra (by $[X,Y]:=XY-YX$ ) has a left adjoint ${\mathfrak {g}}\mapsto U({\mathfrak {g}})$ , called the **universal enveloping algebra**.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] be the tensor algebra on ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , also called the free associative algebra on the vector space ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Here $\otimes$ denotes the tensor product of *F*-vector spaces.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Let *I* be the two-sided ideal in $T({\mathfrak {g}})$ generated by the elements $XY-YX-[X,Y]$ for $X,Y\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ ; then the universal enveloping algebra is the quotient ring $U({\mathfrak {g}})=T({\mathfrak {g}})/I$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] It satisfies the Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem: if $e_{1},\ldots ,e_{n}$ is a basis for ${\mathfrak {g}}$ as an *F*-vector space, then a basis for $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is given by all ordered products $e_{1}^{i_{1}}\cdots e_{n}^{i_{n}}$ with $i_{1},\ldots ,i_{n}$ natural numbers.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In particular, the map ${\mathfrak {g}}\to U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is injective.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Representations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ are equivalent to modules over the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The fact that ${\mathfrak {g}}\to U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is injective implies that every Lie algebra (possibly of infinite dimension) has a faithful representation (of infinite dimension), namely its representation on $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This also shows that every Lie algebra is contained in the Lie algebra associated to some associative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The representation theory of Lie algebras plays an important role in various parts of theoretical physics.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] There, one considers operators on the space of states that satisfy certain natural commutation relations.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] These commutation relations typically come from a symmetry of the problem—specifically, they are the relations of the Lie algebra of the relevant symmetry group.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] An example is the angular momentum operators, whose commutation relations are those of the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {so}}(3)$ of the rotation group $\mathrm {SO} (3)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Typically, the space of states is far from being irreducible under the pertinent operators, but one can attempt to decompose it into irreducible pieces.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In doing so, one needs to know the irreducible representations of the given Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In the study of the hydrogen atom, for example, quantum mechanics textbooks classify (more or less explicitly) the finite-dimensional irreducible representations of the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {so}}(3)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Lie algebras can be classified to some extent.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This is a powerful approach to the classification of Lie groups.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Analogously to abelian, nilpotent, and solvable groups, one can define abelian, nilpotent, and solvable Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is *abelian* if the Lie bracket vanishes; that is, [*x*,*y*] = 0 for all *x* and *y* in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In particular, the Lie algebra of an abelian Lie group (such as the group $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ under addition or the torus group $\mathbb {T} ^{n}$ ) is abelian.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Every finite-dimensional abelian Lie algebra over a field F is isomorphic to $F^{n}$ for some $n\geq 0$ , meaning an *n*-dimensional vector space with Lie bracket zero.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A more general class of Lie algebras is defined by the vanishing of all commutators of given length.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] First, the *commutator subalgebra* (or *derived subalgebra*) of a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is $[{\mathfrak {g}},{\mathfrak {g}}]$ , meaning the linear subspace spanned by all brackets $[x,y]$ with $x,y\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The commutator subalgebra is an ideal in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , in fact the smallest ideal such that the quotient Lie algebra is abelian.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] It is analogous to the commutator subgroup of a group.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Every finite-dimensional Lie algebra over a field has a unique maximal solvable ideal, called its radical.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Under the Lie correspondence, nilpotent (respectively, solvable) Lie groups correspond to nilpotent (respectively, solvable) Lie algebras over $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For example, for a positive integer *n* and a field *F* of characteristic zero, the radical of ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n,F)$ is its center, the 1-dimensional subspace spanned by the identity matrix.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] An example of a solvable Lie algebra is the space ${\mathfrak {b}}_{n}$ of upper-triangular matrices in ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n)$ ; this is not nilpotent when $n\geq 2$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] An example of a nilpotent Lie algebra is the space ${\mathfrak {u}}_{n}$ of strictly upper-triangular matrices in ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n)$ ; this is not abelian when $n\geq 3$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is called *simple* if it is not abelian and the only ideals in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ are 0 and ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (In particular, a one-dimensional—necessarily abelian—Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is by definition not simple, even though its only ideals are 0 and ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .) A finite-dimensional Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is called *semisimple* if the only solvable ideal in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is 0.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In characteristic zero, a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is semisimple if and only if it is isomorphic to a product of simple Lie algebras, ${\mathfrak {g}}\cong {\mathfrak {g}}_{1}\times \cdots \times {\mathfrak {g}}_{r}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For example, the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {sl}}(n,F)$ is simple for every $n\geq 2$ and every field *F* of characteristic zero (or just of characteristic not dividing *n*).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {su}}(n)$ over $\mathbb {R}$ is simple for every $n\geq 2$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {so}}(n)$ over $\mathbb {R}$ is simple if $n=3$ or $n\geq 5$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The concept of semisimplicity for Lie algebras is closely related with the complete reducibility (semisimplicity) of their representations.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] When the ground field *F* has characteristic zero, every finite-dimensional representation of a semisimple Lie algebra is semisimple (that is, a direct sum of irreducible representations).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A finite-dimensional Lie algebra over a field of characteristic zero is called reductive if its adjoint representation is semisimple.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Every reductive Lie algebra is isomorphic to the product of an abelian Lie algebra and a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] where *F* denotes the center of ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n,F)$ , the 1-dimensional subspace spanned by the identity matrix.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Since the special linear Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {sl}}(n,F)$ is simple, ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n,F)$ contains few ideals: only 0, the center *F*, ${\mathfrak {sl}}(n,F)$ , and all of ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n,F)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Cartan's criterion (by Élie Cartan) gives conditions for a finite-dimensional Lie algebra of characteristic zero to be solvable or semisimple.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] where tr denotes the trace of a linear operator.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Namely: a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is semisimple if and only if the Killing form is nondegenerate.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The Levi decomposition asserts that every finite-dimensional Lie algebra over a field of characteristic zero is a semidirect product of its solvable radical and a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Moreover, a semisimple Lie algebra in characteristic zero is a product of simple Lie algebras, as mentioned above.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This focuses attention on the problem of classifying the simple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The simple Lie algebras of finite dimension over an algebraically closed field *F* of characteristic zero were classified by Killing and Cartan in the 1880s and 1890s, using root systems.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Namely, every simple Lie algebra is of type A*n*, B*n*, C*n*, D*n*, E6, E7, E8, F4, or G2.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The other five are known as the exceptional Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The classification of finite-dimensional simple Lie algebras over $\mathbb {R}$ is more complicated, but it was also solved by Cartan (see simple Lie group for an equivalent classification).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] One can analyze a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over $\mathbb {R}$ by considering its complexification ${\mathfrak {g}}\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In the years leading up to 2004, the finite-dimensional simple Lie algebras over an algebraically closed field of characteristic $p>3$ were classified by Richard Earl Block, Robert Lee Wilson, Alexander Premet, and Helmut Strade.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] (See restricted Lie algebra#Classification of simple Lie algebras.) It turns out that there are many more simple Lie algebras in positive characteristic than in characteristic zero.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Although Lie algebras can be studied in their own right, historically they arose as a means to study Lie groups.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The relationship between Lie groups and Lie algebras can be summarized as follows.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Each Lie group determines a Lie algebra over $\mathbb {R}$ (concretely, the tangent space at the identity).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Conversely, for every finite-dimensional Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , there is a connected Lie group G with Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This is Lie's third theorem; see the Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff formula.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This Lie group is not determined uniquely; however, any two Lie groups with the same Lie algebra are *locally isomorphic*, and more strongly, they have the same universal cover.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For instance, the special orthogonal group SO(3) and the special unitary group SU(2) have isomorphic Lie algebras, but SU(2) is a simply connected double cover of SO(3).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For *simply connected* Lie groups, there is a complete correspondence: taking the Lie algebra gives an equivalence of categories from simply connected Lie groups to Lie algebras of finite dimension over $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The correspondence between Lie algebras and Lie groups is used in several ways, including in the classification of Lie groups and the representation theory of Lie groups.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For finite-dimensional representations, there is an equivalence of categories between representations of a real Lie algebra and representations of the corresponding simply connected Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] This simplifies the representation theory of Lie groups: it is often easier to classify the representations of a Lie algebra, using linear algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Every connected Lie group is isomorphic to its universal cover modulo a discrete central subgroup.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] So classifying Lie groups becomes simply a matter of counting the discrete subgroups of the center, once the Lie algebra is known.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For example, the real semisimple Lie algebras were classified by Cartan, and so the classification of semisimple Lie groups is well understood.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For infinite-dimensional Lie algebras, Lie theory works less well.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The exponential map need not be a local homeomorphism (for example, in the diffeomorphism group of the circle, there are diffeomorphisms arbitrarily close to the identity that are not in the image of the exponential map).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Moreover, in terms of the existing notions of infinite-dimensional Lie groups, some infinite-dimensional Lie algebras do not come from any group.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Lie theory also does not work so neatly for infinite-dimensional representations of a finite-dimensional group.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Even for the additive group $G=\mathbb {R}$ , an infinite-dimensional representation of G can usually not be differentiated to produce a representation of its Lie algebra on the same space, or vice versa.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The theory of Harish-Chandra modules is a more subtle relation between infinite-dimensional representations for groups and Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Given a complex Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , a real Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}_{0}$ is said to be a *real form* of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ if the complexification ${\mathfrak {g}}_{0}\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ is isomorphic to ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A real form need not be unique; for example, ${\mathfrak {sl}}(2,\mathbb {C} )$ has two real forms up to isomorphism, ${\mathfrak {sl}}(2,\mathbb {R} )$ and ${\mathfrak {su}}(2)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Given a semisimple complex Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , a *split form* of it is a real form that splits; i.e., it has a Cartan subalgebra which acts via an adjoint representation with real eigenvalues.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A split form exists and is unique (up to isomorphism).
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A *compact form* is a real form that is the Lie algebra of a compact Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A compact form exists and is also unique up to isomorphism.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra may be equipped with additional structures that are compatible with the Lie bracket.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For example, a graded Lie algebra is a Lie algebra (or more generally a Lie superalgebra) with a compatible grading.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A differential graded Lie algebra also comes with a differential, making the underlying vector space a chain complex.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For example, the homotopy groups of a simply connected topological space form a graded Lie algebra, using the Whitehead product.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] In a related construction, Daniel Quillen used differential graded Lie algebras over the rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ to describe rational homotopy theory in algebraic terms.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The definition of a Lie algebra over a field extends to define a Lie algebra over any commutative ring *R*.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Namely, a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over *R* is an *R*-module with an alternating *R*-bilinear map $[\ ,\ ]\colon {\mathfrak {g}}\times {\mathfrak {g}}\to {\mathfrak {g}}$ that satisfies the Jacobi identity.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] A Lie algebra over the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers is sometimes called a **Lie ring**.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Lie rings are used in the study of finite p-groups (for a prime number *p*) through the *Lazard correspondence*.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The lower central factors of a finite *p*-group are finite abelian *p*-groups.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The direct sum of the lower central factors is given the structure of a Lie ring by defining the bracket to be the commutator of two coset representatives; see the example below.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] p-adic Lie groups are related to Lie algebras over the field $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ of p-adic numbers as well as over the ring $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ of p-adic integers.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Part of Claude Chevalley's construction of the finite groups of Lie type involves showing that a simple Lie algebra over the complex numbers comes from a Lie algebra over the integers, and then (with more care) a group scheme over the integers.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] The definition of a Lie algebra can be reformulated more abstractly in the language of category theory.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Namely, one can define a Lie algebra in terms of linear maps—that is, morphisms in the category of vector spaces—without considering individual elements.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] For the category-theoretic definition of Lie algebras, two braiding isomorphisms are needed.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] where $\mathrm {id}$ is the identity morphism.
[src:lie-algebras/lie-algebra] Several generalizations of a Lie algebra have been proposed, many from physics.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] In mathematics, a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is **nilpotent** if its lower central series terminates in the zero subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] If the lower central series eventually arrives at the zero subalgebra, then the Lie algebra is called nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] The lower central series for Lie algebras is analogous to the lower central series in group theory, and nilpotent Lie algebras are analogs of nilpotent groups.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] The nilpotent Lie algebras are precisely those that can be obtained from abelian Lie algebras, by successive central extensions.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] Note that the definition means that, viewed as a non-associative non-unital algebra, a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent if it is nilpotent as an ideal.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] That is, ad*X* is a nilpotent endomorphism in the usual sense of linear endomorphisms (rather than of Lie algebras).
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] We call such an element *X* in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ **ad-nilpotent**.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] A somewhat easier equivalent condition for the nilpotency of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ : ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent if and only if $\mathrm {ad} \,{\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent (as a Lie algebra).
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] To see this, first observe that (1) implies that $\mathrm {ad} \,{\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent, since the expansion of an (*n* − 1)-fold nested bracket will consist of terms of the form in (1).
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] If $\mathrm {ad} \,{\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent, the last expression is zero for large enough *n*, and accordingly the first.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] But this implies (1), so ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] Also, a finite-dimensional Lie algebra is nilpotent if and only if there exists a descending chain of ideals ${\mathfrak {g}}={\mathfrak {g}}_{0}\supset {\mathfrak {g}}_{1}\supset \cdots \supset {\mathfrak {g}}_{n}=0$ such that $[{\mathfrak {g}},{\mathfrak {g}}_{i}]\subset {\mathfrak {g}}_{i+1}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] If ${\mathfrak {gl}}(k,\mathbb {R} )$ is the set of *k × k* matrices with entries in $\mathbb {R}$ , then the subalgebra consisting of strictly upper triangular matrices is a nilpotent Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] A Cartan subalgebra ${\mathfrak {c}}$ of a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {l}}$ is nilpotent and self-normalizing page 80.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] The self-normalizing condition is equivalent to being the normalizer of a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] This includes all diagonal matrices ${\mathfrak {d}}(n)$ in ${\mathfrak {gl}}(n)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] If a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ has an automorphism of prime period with no fixed points except at 0, then ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] Every nilpotent Lie algebra is solvable.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] This is useful in proving the solvability of a Lie algebra since, in practice, it is usually easier to prove nilpotency (when it holds!) rather than solvability.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] However, in general, the converse of this property is false.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] For example, the subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {gl}}(k,\mathbb {R} )$ (*k* ≥ 2) consisting of upper triangular matrices, ${\mathfrak {b}}(k,\mathbb {R} )$ , is solvable but not nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] If a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent, then all subalgebras and homomorphic images are nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] If the quotient algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}/Z({\mathfrak {g}})$ , where $Z({\mathfrak {g}})$ is the center of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , is nilpotent, then so is ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] This is to say that a central extension of a nilpotent Lie algebra by a nilpotent Lie algebra is nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] Engel's theorem: A finite dimensional Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is nilpotent if and only if all elements of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ are ad-nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] The Killing form of a nilpotent Lie algebra is 0.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] A nonzero nilpotent Lie algebra has an outer automorphism, that is, an automorphism that is not in the image of Ad.
[src:lie-algebras/nilpotent-lie-algebra] The derived subalgebra of a finite dimensional solvable Lie algebra over a field of characteristic 0 is nilpotent.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] In mathematics, a Lie algebra is **semisimple** if it is a direct sum of simple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Throughout the article, unless otherwise stated, a Lie algebra is a finite-dimensional Lie algebra over a field of characteristic 0.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The significance of semisimplicity comes firstly from the Levi decomposition, which states that every finite dimensional Lie algebra is the semidirect product of a solvable ideal (its radical) and a semisimple algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] In particular, there is no nonzero Lie algebra that is both solvable and semisimple.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Semisimple Lie algebras have a very elegant classification, in stark contrast to solvable Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Semisimple Lie algebras over an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero are completely classified by their root system, which are in turn classified by Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Semisimple algebras over non-algebraically closed fields can be understood in terms of those over the algebraic closure, though the classification is somewhat more intricate; see real form for the case of real semisimple Lie algebras, which were classified by Élie Cartan.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Further, the representation theory of semisimple Lie algebras is much cleaner than that for general Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For example, the Jordan decomposition in a semisimple Lie algebra coincides with the Jordan decomposition in its representation; this is not the case for Lie algebras in general.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] In particular, every linear semisimple Lie algebra is a subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {sl}}$ , the special linear Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The study of the structure of ${\mathfrak {sl}}$ constitutes an important part of the representation theory for semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The semisimple Lie algebras over the complex numbers were first classified by Wilhelm Killing (1888–90), though his proof lacked rigor.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] His proof was made rigorous by Élie Cartan (1894) in his Ph.D. thesis, who also classified semisimple real Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] This was subsequently refined, and the present classification by Dynkin diagrams was given by then 22-year-old Eugene Dynkin in 1947.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Some minor modifications have been made (notably by J.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Serre), but the proof is unchanged in its essentials and can be found in any standard reference, such as (Humphreys 1972).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] such that *s* and *n* commute with each other.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Moreover, each of *s* and *n* is a polynomial in *x*.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] This is the Jordan decomposition of *x*.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The above applies to the adjoint representation $\operatorname {ad}$ of a semisimple Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] An element *x* of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is said to be semisimple (resp. nilpotent) if $\operatorname {ad} (x)$ is a semisimple (resp. nilpotent) operator.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] where s is semisimple, n is nilpotent and $[s,n]=0$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Moreover, if $y\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ commutes with *x*, then it commutes with both $s,n$ as well.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] is the Jordan decomposition of ρ(*x*) in the endomorphism algebra of the representation space.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be a (finite-dimensional) semisimple Lie algebra over an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The structure of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ can be described by an adjoint action of a certain distinguished subalgebra on it, a Cartan subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] By definition, a Cartan subalgebra (also called a maximal toral subalgebra) ${\mathfrak {h}}$ of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a maximal subalgebra such that, for each $h\in {\mathfrak {h}}$ , $\operatorname {ad} (h)$ is diagonalizable.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] As it turns out, ${\mathfrak {h}}$ is abelian and so all the operators in $\operatorname {ad} ({\mathfrak {h}})$ are simultaneously diagonalizable.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] where $\Phi$ is the set of all nonzero linear functionals $\alpha$ of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ such that ${\mathfrak {g}}_{\alpha }\neq \{0\}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] (The most difficult item to show is $\dim {\mathfrak {g}}_{\alpha }=1$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The linear functionals in $\Phi$ are called the **roots** of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ relative to ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Note that $s_{\alpha }$ has the properties (1) $s_{\alpha }(\alpha )=-\alpha$ and (2) the fixed-point set is $\{\gamma \in {\mathfrak {h}}^{*}|\gamma (h_{\alpha })=0\}$ , which means that $s_{\alpha }$ is the reflection with respect to the hyperplane corresponding to $\alpha$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The above then says that $\Phi$ is a root system.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Then the $3l$ elements $e_{i},f_{i},h_{i}$ (called **Chevalley generators**) generate ${\mathfrak {g}}$ as a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The converse of this is also true: i.e., the Lie algebra generated by the generators and the relations like the above is a (finite-dimensional) semisimple Lie algebra that has the root space decomposition as above (provided the $[a_{ij}]_{1\leq i,j\leq l}$ is a Cartan matrix).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] In particular, two semisimple Lie algebras are isomorphic if they have the same root system.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The implication of the axiomatic nature of a root system and Serre's theorem is that one can enumerate all possible root systems; hence, "all possible" semisimple Lie algebras (finite-dimensional over an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The **Weyl group** is the group of linear transformations of ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}\simeq {\mathfrak {h}}$ generated by the $s_{\alpha }$ 's.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The Weyl group is an important symmetry of the problem; for example, the weights of any finite-dimensional representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ are invariant under the Weyl group.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] where $d(a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n})$ denotes the diagonal matrix with $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}$ on the diagonal.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] for the vector $e_{ij}$ in ${\mathfrak {sl}}_{n}(\mathbb {C} )$ with the standard (matrix) basis, meaning $e_{ij}$ represents the basis vector in the i -th row and j -th column.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] As noted in #Structure, semisimple Lie algebras over $\mathbb {C}$ (or more generally an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero) are classified by the root system associated to their Cartan subalgebras, and the root systems, in turn, are classified by their Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The restriction $n>1$ in the $D_{n}$ family is needed because ${\mathfrak {so}}_{2}$ is one-dimensional and commutative and therefore not semisimple.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] These Lie algebras are numbered so that *n* is the rank.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Almost all of these semisimple Lie algebras are actually simple and the members of these families are almost all distinct, except for some collisions in small rank.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] These four families, together with five exceptions (E6, E7, E8, F4, and G2), are in fact the *only* simple Lie algebras over the complex numbers.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Every semisimple Lie algebra over an algebraically closed field of characteristic 0 is a direct sum of simple Lie algebras (by definition), and the finite-dimensional simple Lie algebras fall in four families – An, Bn, Cn, and Dn – with five exceptions E6, E7, E8, F4, and G2.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The classification proceeds by considering a Cartan subalgebra (see below) and its adjoint action on the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The root system of the action then both determines the original Lie algebra and must have a very constrained form, which can be classified by the Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] See the section below describing Cartan subalgebras and root systems for more details.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The classification is widely considered one of the most elegant results in mathematics – a brief list of axioms yields, via a relatively short proof, a complete but non-trivial classification with surprising structure.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] This should be compared to the classification of finite simple groups, which is significantly more complicated.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The enumeration of the four families is non-redundant and consists only of simple algebras if $n\geq 1$ for An, $n\geq 2$ for Bn, $n\geq 3$ for Cn, and $n\geq 4$ for Dn.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] If one starts numbering lower, the enumeration is redundant, and one has exceptional isomorphisms between simple Lie algebras, which are reflected in isomorphisms of Dynkin diagrams; the En can also be extended down, but below E6 are isomorphic to other, non-exceptional algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Over a non-algebraically closed field, the classification is more complicated – one classifies simple Lie algebras over the algebraic closure, then for each of these, one classifies simple Lie algebras over the original field which have this form (over the closure).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For example, to classify simple real Lie algebras, one classifies real Lie algebras with a given complexification, which are known as real forms of the complex Lie algebra; this can be done by Satake diagrams, which are Dynkin diagrams with additional data ("decorations").
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Then, as in #Structure, ${\textstyle {\mathfrak {g}}={\mathfrak {h}}\oplus \bigoplus _{\alpha \in \Phi }{\mathfrak {g}}_{\alpha }}$ where $\Phi$ is the root system.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Choose the simple roots in $\Phi$ ; a root $\alpha$ of $\Phi$ is then called positive and is denoted by $\alpha >0$ if it is a linear combination of the simple roots with non-negative integer coefficients.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Let ${\textstyle {\mathfrak {b}}={\mathfrak {h}}\oplus \bigoplus _{\alpha >0}{\mathfrak {g}}_{\alpha }}$ , which is a maximal solvable subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , the Borel subalgebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Let *V* be a (possibly-infinite-dimensional) simple ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] If *V* happens to admit a ${\mathfrak {b}}$ -weight vector $v_{0}$ , then it is unique up to scaling and is called the highest weight vector of *V*.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] It is also an ${\mathfrak {h}}$ -weight vector and the ${\mathfrak {h}}$ -weight of $v_{0}$ , a linear functional of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ , is called the highest weight of *V*.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The basic yet nontrivial facts then are (1) to each linear functional $\mu \in {\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ , there exists a simple ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module $V^{\mu }$ having $\mu$ as its highest weight and (2) two simple modules having the same highest weight are equivalent.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] In short, there exists a bijection between ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ and the set of the equivalence classes of simple ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -modules admitting a Borel-weight vector.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For applications, one is often interested in a finite-dimensional simple ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module (a finite-dimensional irreducible representation).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] This is especially the case when ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is the Lie algebra of a Lie group (or complexification of such), since, via the Lie correspondence, a Lie algebra representation can be integrated to a Lie group representation when the obstructions are overcome.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] A linear functional $\mu$ satisfying the above equivalent condition is called a dominant integral weight.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Hence, in summary, there exists a bijection between the dominant integral weights and the equivalence classes of finite-dimensional simple ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -modules, the result known as the theorem of the highest weight.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The character of a finite-dimensional simple module in turns is computed by the Weyl character formula.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The theorem due to Weyl says that, over a field of characteristic zero, every finite-dimensional module of a semisimple Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is completely reducible; i.e., it is a direct sum of simple ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -modules.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Hence, the above results then apply to finite-dimensional representations of a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For a semisimple Lie algebra over a field that has characteristic zero but is not algebraically closed, there is no general structure theory like the one for those over an algebraically closed field of characteristic zero.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] But over the field of real numbers, there are still the structure results.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be a finite-dimensional real semisimple Lie algebra and ${\mathfrak {g}}^{\mathbb {C} }={\mathfrak {g}}\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ the complexification of it (which is again semisimple).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The real Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is called a real form of ${\mathfrak {g}}^{\mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] A real form is called a compact form if the Killing form on it is negative-definite; it is necessarily the Lie algebra of a compact Lie group (hence, the name).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Suppose ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a compact form and ${\mathfrak {h}}\subset {\mathfrak {g}}$ a maximal abelian subspace.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] One can show (for example, from the fact ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is the Lie algebra of a compact Lie group) that $\operatorname {ad} ({\mathfrak {h}})$ consists of skew-Hermitian matrices, diagonalizable over $\mathbb {C}$ with imaginary eigenvalues.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] where each $\alpha \in \Phi$ is real-valued on $i{\mathfrak {h}}$ ; thus, can be identified with a real-linear functional on the real vector space $i{\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For example, let ${\mathfrak {g}}={\mathfrak {su}}(n)$ and take ${\mathfrak {h}}\subset {\mathfrak {g}}$ the subspace of all diagonal matrices.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] where $E_{ij}$ is the matrix that has 1 on the $(i,j)$ -th spot and zero elsewhere.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Suppose ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is not necessarily a compact form (i.e., the signature of the Killing form is not all negative).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Suppose, moreover, it has a Cartan involution $\theta$ and let ${\mathfrak {g}}={\mathfrak {k}}\oplus {\mathfrak {p}}$ be the eigenspace decomposition of $\theta$ , where ${\mathfrak {k}},{\mathfrak {p}}$ are the eigenspaces for 1 and -1, respectively.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For example, if ${\mathfrak {g}}={\mathfrak {sl}}_{n}\mathbb {R}$ and $\theta$ the negative transpose, then ${\mathfrak {k}}={\mathfrak {so}}(n)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Let ${\mathfrak {a}}\subset {\mathfrak {p}}$ be a maximal abelian subspace.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Now, $\operatorname {ad} ({\mathfrak {p}})$ consists of symmetric matrices (with respect to a suitable inner product) and thus the operators in $\operatorname {ad} ({\mathfrak {a}})$ are simultaneously diagonalizable, with real eigenvalues.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Moreover, $\Phi$ is a root system but not necessarily reduced one (i.e., it can happen $\alpha ,2\alpha$ are both roots).
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] If ${\mathfrak {g}}=\mathrm {sl} (n,\mathbb {C} )$ , then ${\mathfrak {h}}$ may be taken to be the diagonal subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , consisting of diagonal matrices whose diagonal entries sum to zero.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Since ${\mathfrak {h}}$ has dimension $n-1$ , we see that $\mathrm {sl} (n;\mathbb {C} )$ has rank $n-1$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The root vectors X in this case may be taken to be the matrices $E_{i,j}$ with $i\neq j$ , where $E_{i,j}$ is the matrix with a 1 in the $(i,j)$ spot and zeros elsewhere.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] After identifying ${\mathfrak {h}}$ with its dual, the roots become the vectors $\alpha _{i,j}:=e_{i}-e_{j}$ in the space of n -tuples that sum to zero.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] This is the root system known as $A_{n-1}$ in the conventional labeling.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The reflection associated to the root $\alpha _{i,j}$ acts on ${\mathfrak {h}}$ by transposing the i and j diagonal entries.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] The Weyl group is then just the permutation group on n elements, acting by permuting the diagonal entries of matrices in ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Semisimple Lie algebras admit certain generalizations.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Firstly, many statements that are true for semisimple Lie algebras are true more generally for reductive Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Many properties of semisimple Lie algebras depend only on reducibility.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Split Lie algebras have essentially the same representation theory as semisimple Lie algebras over algebraically closed fields, for instance, the splitting Cartan subalgebra playing the same role as the Cartan subalgebra plays over algebraically closed fields.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] This is the approach followed in (Bourbaki 2005), for instance, which classifies representations of split semisimple/reductive Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] A connected Lie group is called semisimple if its Lie algebra is a semisimple Lie algebra, i.e. a direct sum of simple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] It is called reductive if its Lie algebra is a direct sum of simple and trivial (one-dimensional) Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] Reductive groups occur naturally as symmetries of a number of mathematical objects in algebra, geometry, and physics.
[src:lie-algebras/semisimple-lie-algebra] For example, the group $GL_{n}(\mathbb {R} )$ of symmetries of an *n*-dimensional real vector space (equivalently, the group of invertible matrices) is reductive.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In mathematics, the **universal enveloping algebra** of a Lie algebra is the unital associative algebra whose representations correspond precisely to the representations of that Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Universal enveloping algebras are used in the representation theory of Lie groups and Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For example, Verma modules can be constructed as quotients of the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In addition, the enveloping algebra gives a precise definition for the Casimir operators.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Because Casimir operators commute with all elements of a Lie algebra, they can be used to classify representations.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The precise definition also allows the importation of Casimir operators into other areas of mathematics, specifically, those that have a differential algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] They also play a central role in some recent developments in mathematics.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In particular, their dual provides a commutative example of the objects studied in non-commutative geometry, the quantum groups.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This dual can be shown, by the Gelfand–Naimark theorem, to contain the C* algebra of the corresponding Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This relationship generalizes to the idea of Tannaka–Krein duality between compact topological groups and their representations.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] From an analytic viewpoint, the universal enveloping algebra of the Lie algebra of a Lie group may be identified with the algebra of left-invariant differential operators on the group.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] There may be many ways to make such an embedding, but there is a unique "largest" such ${\mathcal {A}}$ , called the universal enveloping algebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The associativity of the universal enveloping algebra can be understood as arising from the associativity of function composition.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Consider the case where ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is just "some non-associative algebra" (without any appeal to it being a Lie algebra).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For any element $a\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ , left-multiplication by a defines a map, that is, a function $L_{a}:{\mathfrak {g}}\to {\mathfrak {g}}.$ The collection of all such maps, using function composition as a product, forms an associative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] An enveloping algebra is an algebra of all such functions $L_{a}$ with function composition as the product.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is manifestly associative, because function composition is associative.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] That this algebra is indeed an algebra over a field, i.e. a vector space, i.e. linear, is also manifest: the $L_{a}$ can be added, and also multiplied by the scalars of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ (usually the reals or the complex numbers, or more generally any ring or field).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] As a vector space, a primary task is to find a vector space basis for this enveloping algebra, and then define function composition in terms of this basis.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] That is, given $a,b\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ one wishes to find $p\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ such that $L_{a}\circ L_{b}=L_{p}$ , and more generally, to find the smallest such set of $p\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ that span the space.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be a Lie algebra, assumed finite-dimensional for simplicity, with basis $X_{1},\ldots X_{n}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Below we will make this "generators and relations" construction more precise by constructing the universal enveloping algebra as a quotient of the tensor algebra over ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] We emphasize that the universal enveloping algebra *is not* the same as (or contained in) the algebra of $2\times 2$ matrices.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For example, the $2\times 2$ matrix E satisfies $E^{2}=0$ , as is easily verified.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] But in the universal enveloping algebra, the element e does not satisfy $e^{2}=0$ because we do not impose this relation in the construction of the enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Indeed, it follows from the Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem (discussed § below) that the elements $1,e,e^{2},e^{3},\ldots$ are all linearly independent in the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In general, elements of the universal enveloping algebra are linear combinations of products of the generators in all possible orders.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Using the defining relations of the universal enveloping algebra, we can always re-order those products in a particular order, say with all the factors of $x_{1}$ first, then factors of $x_{2}$ , etc.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For example, whenever we have a term that contains $x_{2}x_{1}$ (in the "wrong" order), we can use the relations to rewrite this as $x_{1}x_{2}$ plus a linear combination of the $x_{j}$ 's.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Doing this sort of thing repeatedly eventually converts any element into a linear combination of terms in ascending order.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] with the $k_{j}$ 's being non-negative integers, span the enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] (We allow $k_{j}=0$ , meaning that we allow terms in which no factors of $x_{j}$ occur.) The Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem, discussed below, asserts that these elements are linearly independent and thus form a basis for the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In particular, the universal enveloping algebra is always infinite dimensional.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem implies, in particular, that the elements $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ themselves are linearly independent.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is therefore common—if potentially confusing—to identify the $x_{j}$ 's with the generators $X_{j}$ of the original Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] That is to say, we identify the original Lie algebra as the subspace of its universal enveloping algebra spanned by the generators.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Although ${\mathfrak {g}}$ may be an algebra of $n\times n$ matrices, the universal enveloping of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ does not consist of (finite-dimensional) matrices.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In particular, there is no finite-dimensional algebra that contains the universal enveloping of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ ; the universal enveloping algebra is always infinite dimensional.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, in the case of sl(2,C), if we identify our Lie algebra as a subspace of its universal enveloping algebra, we must not interpret E , F and H as $2\times 2$ matrices, but rather as symbols with no further properties (other than the commutation relations).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The formal construction of the universal enveloping algebra takes the above ideas, and wraps them in notation and terminology that makes it more convenient to work with.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The most important difference is that the free associative algebra used in the above is narrowed to the tensor algebra, so that the product of symbols is understood to be the tensor product.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The commutation relations are imposed by constructing a quotient space of the tensor algebra quotiented by the *smallest* two-sided ideal containing elements of the form $x_{i}x_{j}-x_{j}x_{i}-\Sigma c_{ijk}x_{k}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal enveloping algebra is the "largest" unital associative algebra generated by elements of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ with a Lie bracket compatible with the original Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Recall that every Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is in particular a vector space.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, one is free to construct the tensor algebra $T({\mathfrak {g}})$ from it.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The tensor algebra is a free algebra: it simply contains all possible tensor products of all possible vectors in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , without any restrictions whatsoever on those products.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] where $\otimes$ is the tensor product, and $\oplus$ is the direct sum of vector spaces.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Here, *K* is the field over which the Lie algebra is defined.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] From here, through to the remainder of this article, the tensor product is always explicitly shown.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Many authors omit it, since, with practice, its location can usually be inferred from context.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Here, a very explicit approach is adopted, to minimize any possible confusion about the meanings of expressions.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The first step in the construction is to "lift" the Lie bracket from the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ (where it is defined) to the tensor algebra $T({\mathfrak {g}})$ (where it is not), so that one can coherently work with the Lie bracket of two tensors.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is straightforward to verify that the above definition is bilinear and skew-symmetric; one can also show that it obeys the Jacobi identity.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The result of this lifting is that $T({\mathfrak {g}})$ becomes a Poisson algebra: a unital associative algebra with a Lie bracket that is compatible with the original Lie algebra bracket (by construction).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is not the *smallest* such algebra, however; it contains far more elements than needed.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One can get something smaller by projecting back down.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] That is, the Lie bracket defines the equivalence relation used to perform the quotienting.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The result is still a unital associative algebra, and one can still take the Lie bracket of any two members.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Computing the result is straight-forward, if one keeps in mind that each element of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ can be understood as a coset: one just takes the bracket as usual, and searches for the coset that contains the result.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is the *smallest* such algebra; one cannot find anything smaller that still obeys the axioms of an associative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal enveloping algebra is what remains of the tensor algebra after modding out the Poisson algebra structure.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] (This is a non-trivial statement; the tensor algebra has a rather complicated structure: it is, among other things, a Hopf algebra; the Poisson algebra is likewise rather complicated, with many peculiar properties.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is compatible with the tensor algebra, and so the modding can be performed.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The Hopf algebra structure is conserved; this is what leads to its many novel applications, e.g. in string theory.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The construction can be performed in a slightly different (but equivalent) way.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] where all lower-case letters are elements of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Since *I* is an ideal, we can quotient by it.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The above construction focuses on Lie algebras and on the Lie bracket, and its skewness and antisymmetry.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] To some degree, these properties are incidental to the construction.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Consider instead some (arbitrary) algebra (not a Lie algebra) over a vector space, that is, a vector space V endowed with multiplication $m:V\times V\to V$ that takes elements $a\times b\mapsto m(a,b).$ *If* the multiplication is bilinear, then the same construction and definitions can go through.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One starts by lifting m up to $T(V)$ so that the lifted m obeys all of the same properties that the base m does – symmetry or antisymmetry or whatever.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This is consistent precisely because the tensor product is bilinear, and the multiplication is bilinear.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The rest of the lift is performed so as to preserve multiplication as a homomorphism.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This extension is consistent by appeal to a lemma on free objects: since the tensor algebra is a free algebra, any homomorphism on its generating set can be extended to the entire algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Everything else proceeds as described above: upon completion, one has a unital associative algebra; one can take a quotient in either of the two ways described above.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The above is exactly how the universal enveloping algebra for Lie superalgebras is constructed.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One need only to carefully keep track of the sign, when permuting elements.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In this case, the (anti-)commutator of the superalgebra lifts to an (anti-)commuting Poisson bracket.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Another possibility is to use something other than the tensor algebra as the covering algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One such possibility is to use the exterior algebra; that is, to replace every occurrence of the tensor product by the exterior product.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] If the base algebra is a Lie algebra, then the result is the Gerstenhaber algebra; it is the exterior algebra of the corresponding Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] As before, it has a grading naturally coming from the grading on the exterior algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The construction has also been generalized for Malcev algebras, Bol algebras and left alternative algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal enveloping algebra, or rather the universal enveloping algebra together with the canonical map $h\colon {\mathfrak {g}}\to U({\mathfrak {g}})$ , possesses a universal property.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] to a unital associative algebra *A* (with Lie bracket in *A* given by the commutator).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] where $h:{\mathfrak {g}}\to U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is the canonical map.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] (The map h is obtained by embedding ${\mathfrak {g}}$ into its tensor algebra and then composing with the quotient map to the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] To put it differently, if $\varphi \colon {\mathfrak {g}}\rightarrow A$ is a linear map into a unital algebra A satisfying $\varphi ([X,Y])=\varphi (X)\varphi (Y)-\varphi (Y)\varphi (X)$ , then $\varphi$ extends to an algebra homomorphism of ${\widehat {\varphi }}:U({\mathfrak {g}})\to A$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal property of the enveloping algebra immediately implies that every representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ acting on a vector space V extends uniquely to a representation of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] (Take $A=\mathrm {End} (V)$ .) This observation is important because it allows (as discussed below) the Casimir elements to act on V .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] These operators (from the center of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ ) act as scalars and provide important information about the representations.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The quadratic Casimir element is of particular importance in this regard.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Although the canonical construction, given above, can be applied to other algebras, the result, in general, does not have the universal property.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, for example, when the construction is applied to Jordan algebras, the resulting enveloping algebra contains the special Jordan algebras, but not the exceptional ones: that is, it does not envelope the Albert algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Likewise, the Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem, below, constructs a basis for an enveloping algebra; it just won't be universal.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Similar remarks hold for the Lie superalgebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem gives a precise description of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This can be done in either one of two different ways: either by reference to an explicit vector basis on the Lie algebra, or in a coordinate-free fashion.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One way is to suppose that the Lie algebra can be given a totally ordered basis, that is, it is the free vector space of a totally ordered set.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Let $h:{\mathfrak {g}}\to T({\mathfrak {g}})$ be the injection into the tensor algebra; this is used to give the tensor algebra a basis as well.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem then states that one can obtain a basis for $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ from the above, by enforcing the total order of *X* onto the algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] where $a\leq b\leq \cdots \leq c$ , the ordering being that of total order on the set *X*.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The proof of the theorem involves noting that, if one starts with out-of-order basis elements, these can always be swapped by using the commutator (together with the structure constants).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The hard part of the proof is establishing that the final result is unique and independent of the order in which the swaps were performed.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This basis should be easily recognized as the basis of a symmetric algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] That is, the underlying vector spaces of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ and the symmetric algebra are isomorphic, and it is the PBW theorem that shows that this is so.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] See, however, the section on the algebra of symbols, below, for a more precise statement of the nature of the isomorphism.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is useful, perhaps, to split the process into two steps.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In the first step, one constructs the free Lie algebra: this is what one gets, if one mods out by all commutators, without specifying what the values of the commutators are.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One can also state the theorem in a coordinate-free fashion, avoiding the use of total orders and basis elements.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This is convenient when there are difficulties in defining the basis vectors, as there can be for infinite-dimensional Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It also gives a more natural form that is more easily extended to other kinds of algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] First, a notation is needed for an ascending sequence of subspaces of the tensor algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] More precisely, this is a filtered algebra, since the filtration preserves the algebraic properties of the subspaces.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This is the space $U_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ modulo all of the subspaces $U_{n}{\mathfrak {g}}$ of strictly smaller filtration degree.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Note that $G_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ is *not at all* the same as the leading term $U^{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ of the filtration, as one might naively surmise.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is not constructed through a set subtraction mechanism associated with the filtration.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Quotienting $U_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ by $U_{m-1}{\mathfrak {g}}$ has the effect of setting all Lie commutators defined in $U_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ to zero.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One can see this by observing that the commutator of a pair of elements whose products lie in $U_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ actually gives an element in $U_{m-1}{\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This is perhaps not immediately obvious: to get this result, one must repeatedly apply the commutation relations, and turn the crank.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The essence of the Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem is that it is always possible to do this, and that the result is unique.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Since commutators of elements whose products are defined in $U_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ lie in $U_{m-1}{\mathfrak {g}}$ , the quotienting that defines $G_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ has the effect of setting all commutators to zero.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] What PBW states is that the commutator of elements in $G_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ is necessarily zero.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] What is left are the elements that are not expressible as commutators.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In this way, one is lead immediately to the symmetric algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This is the algebra where all commutators vanish.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It can be defined as a filtration $S_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ of symmetric tensor products $\operatorname {Sym} ^{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Its limit is the symmetric algebra $S({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is constructed by appeal to the same notion of naturality as before.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, one can view the Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem as stating that $G({\mathfrak {g}})$ is isomorphic to the symmetric algebra $S({\mathfrak {g}})$ , both as a vector space *and* as a commutative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The $G_{m}{\mathfrak {g}}$ also form a filtered algebra; its limit is $G({\mathfrak {g}}).$ This is the associated graded algebra of the filtration.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] To emphasize this, the notation $\operatorname {gr} U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is sometimes used for $G({\mathfrak {g}}),$ serving to remind that it is the filtered algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The theorem, applied to Jordan algebras, yields the exterior algebra, rather than the symmetric algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In essence, the construction zeros out the anti-commutators.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The resulting algebra is *an* enveloping algebra, but is not universal.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] As mentioned above, it fails to envelop the exceptional Jordan algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Suppose G is a real Lie group with Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Following the modern approach, we may identify ${\mathfrak {g}}$ with the space of left-invariant vector fields (i.e., first-order left-invariant differential operators).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Specifically, if we initially think of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ as the tangent space to G at the identity, then each vector in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ has a unique left-invariant extension.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] We then identify the vector in the tangent space with the associated left-invariant vector field.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Now, the commutator (as differential operators) of two left-invariant vector fields is again a vector field and again left-invariant.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] We can then define the bracket operation on ${\mathfrak {g}}$ as the commutator on the associated left-invariant vector fields.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This definition agrees with any other standard definition of the bracket structure on the Lie algebra of a Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] We may then consider left-invariant differential operators of arbitrary order.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Every such operator A can be expressed (non-uniquely) as a linear combination of products of left-invariant vector fields.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The collection of all left-invariant differential operators on G forms an algebra, denoted $D(G)$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It can be shown that $D(G)$ is isomorphic to the universal enveloping algebra $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In the case that ${\mathfrak {g}}$ arises as the Lie algebra of a real Lie group, one can use left-invariant differential operators to give an analytic proof of the Poincaré–Birkhoff–Witt theorem.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Specifically, the algebra $D(G)$ of left-invariant differential operators is generated by elements (the left-invariant vector fields) that satisfy the commutation relations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, by the universal property of the enveloping algebra, $D(G)$ is a quotient of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, if the PBW basis elements are linearly independent in $D(G)$ —which one can establish analytically—they must certainly be linearly independent in $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The underlying vector space of $S({\mathfrak {g}})$ may be given a new algebra structure so that $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ and $S({\mathfrak {g}})$ are isomorphic *as associative algebras*.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This leads to the concept of the **algebra of symbols** $\star ({\mathfrak {g}})$ : the space of symmetric polynomials, endowed with a product, the $\star$ , that places the algebraic structure of the Lie algebra onto what is otherwise a standard associative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] That is, what the PBW theorem obscures (the commutation relations) the algebra of symbols restores into the spotlight.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The algebra is obtained by taking elements of $S({\mathfrak {g}})$ and replacing each generator $e_{i}$ by an indeterminate, commuting variable $t_{i}$ to obtain the space of symmetric polynomials $K[t_{i}]$ over the field K .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Indeed, the correspondence is trivial: one simply substitutes the symbol $t_{i}$ for $e_{i}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The resulting polynomial is called the **symbol** of the corresponding element of $S({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] that replaces each symbol $t_{i}$ by $e_{i}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] An explicit expression for this product can be given: this is the **Berezin formula**.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It follows essentially from the Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff formula for the product of two elements of a Lie group.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] and $m^{i}$ is just m in the chosen basis.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal enveloping algebra of the Heisenberg algebra is the Weyl algebra (modulo the relation that the center be the unit); here, the $\star$ product is called the Moyal product.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal enveloping algebra preserves the representation theory: the representations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ correspond in a one-to-one manner to the modules over $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In more abstract terms, the abelian category of all representations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is isomorphic to the abelian category of all left modules over $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] is just the canonical embedding (with subscripts, respectively for algebras one and two).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is straightforward to verify that this embedding lifts, given the prescription above.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] See, however, the discussion of the bialgebra structure in the article on tensor algebras for a review of some of the finer points of doing so: in particular, the shuffle product employed there corresponds to the Wigner-Racah coefficients, i.e. the 6j and 9j-symbols, etc.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Also important is that the universal enveloping algebra of a free Lie algebra is isomorphic to the free associative algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Construction of representations typically proceeds by building the Verma modules of the highest weights.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In a typical context where ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is acting by *infinitesimal transformations*, the elements of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ act like differential operators, of all orders.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For a finite-dimensional semisimple Lie algebra, the Casimir operators form a distinguished basis from the center $Z(U({\mathfrak {g}}))$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] From the PBW theorem, it is clear that all central elements are linear combinations of symmetric homogeneous polynomials in the basis elements $e_{a}$ of the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The Casimir invariants are the irreducible homogeneous polynomials of a given, fixed degree.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] where there are m terms in the tensor product, and $\kappa ^{ab\cdots c}$ is a completely symmetric tensor of order m belonging to the adjoint representation.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] where $\kappa ^{ij}$ is the inverse matrix of the Killing form $\kappa _{ij}.$ That the Casimir operator $C_{(2)}$ belongs to the center $Z(U({\mathfrak {g}}))$ follows from the fact that the Killing form is invariant under the adjoint action.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The center of the universal enveloping algebra of a simple Lie algebra is given in detail by the Harish-Chandra isomorphism.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The number of algebraically independent Casimir operators of a finite-dimensional semisimple Lie algebra is equal to the rank of that algebra, i.e. is equal to the rank of the Cartan–Weyl basis.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For a *d*-dimensional vector space *V*, recall that the determinant is the completely antisymmetric tensor on $V^{\otimes d}$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] for elements $x\in {\mathfrak {g}}.$ The non-zero roots of this characteristic polynomial (that are roots for all *x*) form the root system of the algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] In general, there are only *r* such roots; this is the rank of the algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This implies that the highest value of *n* for which the $p_{n}(x)$ is non-vanishing is *r*.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The $p_{n}(x)$ are homogeneous polynomials of degree *d* − *n*.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] that is, a $\kappa$ is a tensor of rank $m=d-n$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] By linearity and the commutativity of addition, i.e. that $\operatorname {ad} _{x+y}=\operatorname {ad} _{y+x},$ , one concludes that this tensor must be completely symmetric.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This tensor is exactly the Casimir invariant of order *m*.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The center $Z({\mathfrak {g}})$ corresponded to those elements $z\in Z({\mathfrak {g}})$ for which $\operatorname {ad} _{x}(z)=0$ for all *x*; by the above, these clearly corresponds to the roots of the characteristic equation.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One concludes that the roots form a space of rank *r* and that the Casimir invariants span this space.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The rotation group SO(3) is of rank one, and thus has one Casimir operator.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] It is three-dimensional, and thus the Casimir operator must have order (3 − 1) = 2 i.e. be quadratic.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Of course, this is the Lie algebra of $A_{1}.$ As an elementary exercise, one can compute this directly.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The quadratic term can be read off as $\kappa ^{ij}=\delta ^{ij}$ , and so the squared angular momentum operator for the rotation group is that Casimir operator.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] A key observation during the construction of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ above was that it was a differential algebra, by dint of the fact that any derivation on the Lie algebra can be lifted to $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Thus, one is led to a ring of pseudo-differential operators, from which one can construct Casimir invariants.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] If the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ acts on a space of linear operators, such as in Fredholm theory, then one can construct Casimir invariants on the corresponding space of operators.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The quadratic Casimir operator corresponds to an elliptic operator.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] If the Lie algebra acts on a differentiable manifold, then each Casimir operator corresponds to a higher-order differential on the cotangent manifold, the second-order differential being the most common and most important.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] If the action of the algebra is isometric, as would be the case for Riemannian or pseudo-Riemannian manifolds endowed with a metric and the symmetry groups SO(N) and SO (P, Q), respectively, one can then contract upper and lower indices (with the metric tensor) to obtain more interesting structures.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] For the quadratic Casimir invariant, this is the Laplacian.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Quartic Casimir operators allow one to square the stress–energy tensor, giving rise to the Yang-Mills action.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The Coleman–Mandula theorem restricts the form that these can take, when one considers ordinary Lie algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] However, the Lie superalgebras are able to evade the premises of the Coleman–Mandula theorem, and can be used to mix together space and internal symmetries.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] If ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is *abelian* (that is, the bracket is always 0), then $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is commutative; and if a basis of the vector space ${\mathfrak {g}}$ has been chosen, then $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ can be identified with the polynomial algebra over *K*, with one variable per basis element.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] To relate the above two cases: if ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a vector space *V* as abelian Lie algebra, the left-invariant differential operators are the constant coefficient operators, which are indeed a polynomial algebra in the partial derivatives of first order.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The center $Z({\mathfrak {g}})$ consists of the left- and right- invariant differential operators; this, in the case of *G* not commutative, is often not generated by first-order operators (see for example Casimir operator of a semi-simple Lie algebra).
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Another characterization in Lie group theory is of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ as the convolution algebra of distributions supported only at the identity element *e* of *G*.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The algebra of differential operators in *n* variables with polynomial coefficients may be obtained starting with the Lie algebra of the Heisenberg group.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] See Weyl algebra for this; one must take a quotient, so that the central elements of the Lie algebra act as prescribed scalars.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The universal enveloping algebra of a finite-dimensional Lie algebra is a filtered quadratic algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] The construction of the group algebra for a given group is in many ways analogous to constructing the universal enveloping algebra for a given Lie algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Both constructions are universal and translate representation theory into module theory.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Furthermore, both group algebras and universal enveloping algebras carry natural comultiplications that turn them into Hopf algebras.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] This is made precise in the article on the tensor algebra: the tensor algebra has a Hopf algebra structure on it, and because the Lie bracket is consistent with (obeys the consistency conditions for) that Hopf structure, it is inherited by the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Given a Lie group *G*, one can construct the vector space C(*G*) of continuous complex-valued functions on *G*, and turn it into a C*-algebra.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] Now, the Gelfand–Naimark theorem essentially states that every commutative Hopf algebra is isomorphic to the Hopf algebra of continuous functions on some compact topological group *G*—the theory of compact topological groups and the theory of commutative Hopf algebras are the same.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] These ideas can then be extended to the non-commutative case.
[src:lie-algebras/universal-enveloping-algebra] One starts by defining the quasi-triangular Hopf algebras, and then performing what is called a quantum deformation to obtain the **quantum universal enveloping algebra**, or quantum group, for short.
